THE BELGIAN Communem-The people of Northern Gaul, includ- ing Flanders and the Netherlands, were far remote from any country hith- erto occupied by the Roman arms. They lived arnid forests and swamps hard to penetrate3 they claimed kindred with the German tribes rather than with the more fickle and effeminate Celts3 and they had a fierce and resolute spirit of independcnce, like that which the Dutch exhibited long after in the same regions, against the armies of Spain* The Belgian tribes, and partic· ularly the Nervii, appear in this confederation to have offered to Caesara more formidable and desperate resistance than any he met elsewhere, until the great rising of rac. 52; and when their spirit was once broken, the con· quest of Gaul was simply a question of time.

R. 3. ll.; H. 445. 4.-demonstravimus . .. dixeramus. The Romans were very precise in indicating the relation of actions to one another in point of time. When one must be completed before another begins, the former is almost invariably expressed by a tense of completed action. Here the perfect, demonstravimus, implies an act (Bk. 1. Chap. 54) done before the time of writing; the pluperfect‚ dixeramus, an act (Bk. Ι. Chap. 1) that took place before the letters and rumors came. Of course, to the writer the time of writing was present. and at that time the acts denoted by atterebantur and fiebat were in the past.
